    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_681864599" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/681864599" />
    <a title="M" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13167-m"><img alt="M" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/681864599?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="M" class="user" itemprop="url" name="M" href="/user/show/13167-m">M</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer681864599" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2907183938003595518">As a child, I insisted that I would never wear an engagement ring (I was equally sure I would never get married. Need I say I type this wearing the diamond my husband gave me when he proposed?). To me, they stripped marriage of everything it should be, and highjacked it with all of the shallow, materialistic non values of the western world. This was only exacerbated in my all women&apos;s college (picture Wellesley circa 1952, only fifty years later) where the buzz in the computer lab was typically o</span>
  <span id="freeText2907183938003595518" style="display:none">As a child, I insisted that I would never wear an engagement ring (I was equally sure I would never get married. Need I say I type this wearing the diamond my husband gave me when he proposed?). To me, they stripped marriage of everything it should be, and highjacked it with all of the shallow, materialistic non values of the western world. This was only exacerbated in my all women's college (picture Wellesley circa 1952, only fifty years later) where the buzz in the computer lab was typically over the latest display on the tiffany website if not the live rock featured on a the nearest manicured hand. And I didn't even know about this whole blood diamond thing!<br />At the heart (in more ways than one) of Sullivan's novel is the history behind not only diamonds as a dangerous and ruthless trade but also how they came to be the center of a proposal. The amount of marketing that turned marriage into a commercial enterprise makes Mother's Day look like an ordinary Sunday. Francie (based on a real person - who knew?) is a renegade woman in the 30s who refuses to marry and instead devotes her life to pursuing a career in advertising. She puts diamonds on the map with her slogan - A diamond is forever - and so the woman who has no interest in matrimony ends up spending the bulk of her time spinning soft ads that sell exactly that.<br />This thread of marriage and rings runs throughout the other narratives, each one taking place in a different decade, each one eventually connecting to each other. The characters were often extreme - Kate is another anti marriage/weddings person, yet her opinions are often sanctimonious and hard to take even if at the core I agree, and Delphine, while an excellent representative of a French ex pat, has a love affair that is beyond any level of realism - but I found myself enjoying each thread of the story, to varying degrees, and being happy to pick up this book much as I was with Sullivan's previous work, Maine - this one, to me had more substance.<br />After I read this I saw somewhere that it has already been contracted to become a movie, and I thought, that makes sense - reading it felt like watching one of those movies - you know which kind I mean, they have four seemingly unrelated story lines that end up coming together and they feature ridiculously good looking famous people.<br />Anyway for all that it read like a movie, I have to say that I really enjoyed this. I feel like Sullivan has come a long, long way from Commencement. While Engagements had more than its share of cheesy moments as well as extremes to prove a point rather than natural turns of character, it is an enjoyable, undemanding read that raises interesting points.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2907183938003595518" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


